data.content:
The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already provides `IFileSystem` with mock support. No need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # in your test project
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

For example, your `ReportGenerator` would become:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

The key mapping is:
| Before (static) | After (injected) |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(path)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(path, content)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content)` |
| `Directory.Exists(path)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path)` |

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/tmp/reports/existing.txt", new MockFileData("old report") }
});

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

`MockFileSystem` gives you a full in-memory file system — no temp directories, no cleanup, and tests run in parallel safely.

> **Note:** Your `ReportGenerator` also uses `DateTime.UtcNow`, `Environment.*`, and `Console.WriteLine`. For those, consider injecting `TimeProvider` (built-in on .NET 10) and custom `IEnvironmentProvider` / `IConsole` wrappers. Want me to generate those too?
